{
  "answer": "**Modes of Divine Communication**\nSurah Ash-Shura 42:51 establishes that God does not speak to any human being face-to-face [1]. Instead, divine communication occurs through three specific methods: direct revelation, speaking from behind a partition or veil, or sending an angelic messenger to reveal God's will [1, 2]. This ayah anchors the theological understanding that prophets receive guidance through protected, divine channels [1]. \n\n**The Seal of the Prophets**\nSurah Al-Ahzab 33:40 defines the finality of prophethood by declaring that Prophet Muhammad is the Messenger of God and the \"seal\" or very last of the prophets [3]. The sources emphasize that while previous prophets were sent exclusively to their own nations, Prophet Muhammad was sent to all of mankind, officially closing the line of prophets [4, 5]. The Prophet illustrated this theological concept by comparing the history of prophethood to a beautifully built house, with himself acting as the final brick that completes the structure [6].\n\n**The Nature and Continuity of Prophethood**\nSeveral other ayat contextually anchor the study of how and why prophets were sent:\n*   **A Unified Message:** Surah Al-Anbiya 21:25 confirms that every messenger prior to Muhammad received the exact same core revelation: that there is no deity except God, and He alone must be worshipped [7]. \n*   **The Divine Covenant:** Surah Al-Ahzab 33:7 outlines that God took a solemn covenant from all the major prophets, linking Muhammad directly with Noah, Abraham, Moses, and Jesus in a shared mission [8].\n*   **Humanity of the Prophets:** The Qur'an emphasizes that messengers were not angels or immortal beings; they were mortal men who ate food and walked in the markets [9, 10].\n*   **The Purpose of Revelation:** God sent these messengers as bringers of good tidings and warners, ensuring that mankind would have no argument or excuse against God after their arrival [11].",
  "conversation_id": "b75c54d4-0ca8-4686-8f68-eef116d359e6",
